{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Pur\u00e9ed fava beans and cooked chicory are a classic pairing in Italy; for this version, almost any kind of hearty bitter lettuce will work.", "abstract": null, "section_name": "Health", "print_page": null, "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "SHULMAN", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Martha", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "Rose"}], "original": "By MARTHA ROSE SHULMAN"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/10/health/nutrition/white-beans-with-chicory.html", "lead_paragraph": "This is inspired by a classic dish from Apulia, the heel of the Italian boot. The authentic dish is a warm pur\u00e9e of skinned dried fava beans, served with cooked greens, usually chicory, a bitter green that is in the same family as escarole. If you are getting big heads of escarole or another hearty bitter lettuce called Batavia in your C.S.A. baskets, use the tough outer leaves for this and save the tender hearts for salads. 1 pound dried cannellini beans, washed and picked over, soaked for 4 to 6 hours in 2 quarts water and drained", "headline": {"main": "White Beans With Chicory", "kicker": "RECIPES FOR HEALTH"}, "_id": "4fd2a99a8eb7c8105d8950f0", "word_count": 2419, "multimedia": [{"height": 75, "url": "images/2012/05/10/health/nutrition/10recipehealth/10recipehealth-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2012/05/10/health/nutrition/10recipehealth/10recipehealth-thumbStandard.jpg", "hasthumbnail": "Y", "thumbnailwidth": 75, "thumbnailheight": 75}, "subtype": "thumbnail", "width": 75, "type": "image"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2012/05/10/health/nutrition/10recipehealth/10recipehealth-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2012/05/10/health/nutrition/10recipehealth/10recipehealth-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": 600, "xlargeheight": 400, "hasxlarge": "Y"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}], "pub_date": "2012-05-08T00:00:00Z", "source": "The New York